WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.720
This is Hadley Wickham, and take it away.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:12.240
Thanks Mara.

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:18.559
So I wanted to talk, not about visualization, unfortunately, but a little bit about the

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:22.240
Tidyverse generally.

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.719
So I wanted to give you kind of a little bit of an update, like kind of where things are

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:33.279
going in the Tidyverse, where are we today, talk a little bit about TidyEval, which I

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:39.439
know has caused some unhappiness in various places in the R community, and then talk a

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:45.200
little bit about what we're doing to address some of those problems in the future.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:49.560
So I made a few plots to kind of show how things are going.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:55.200
So the first one is just the cumulative number of package downloads.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:59.959
So 2018 on the left, 2019 on the right.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:04.440
This data is not super trustworthy, I would love to believe that three quarters of a million

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:12.199
people decided to use the Tidyverse, I guess, basically on my birthday.

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:17.639
But I think the main takeaway here is that the numbers are continuing to grow, really

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:22.519
just continues to amaze me how many people find these tools useful.

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:27.360
The other thing that I think is really fascinating is that 2019 was the first year that more

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:29.559
people downloaded dplyr than ggplot2.

00:01:29.559 --> 00:01:35.360
I don't really know what that means, but I think that's kind of interesting.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:37.599
So who works on these packages?

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:40.800
So my team at RStudio encompasses a bunch of people.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:48.239
So Jim Hester, Thomas Lynn Peterson, Gabor Ciardi, Romain Francois, Jenny Bryan, Max

00:01:48.239 --> 00:01:53.519
Kuhn, Leonel Henry, me, Mara Averick, and Davis Horne.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:02:03.279
And very, very soon we'll be joined by Julia Selge on Monday.

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:07.959
But as well as us, there's also a huge number of people in the community who contribute

00:02:07.959 --> 00:02:09.279
to the Tidyverse.

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:16.839
And last year, in fact, we had 236 unique contributors, which is just so amazing and

00:02:16.839 --> 00:02:19.960
feels so wonderful to me.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:25.320
And so I also made this chart of the number of unique contributors comparing 2018 to the

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:26.919
last year.

00:02:26.919 --> 00:02:32.880
We ended up with quite a few more unique contributors last year because of two main events.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:37.479
These are the Tidyverse developer days, which we did for the first time last year, but we're

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:40.279
going to be continuing to do them a lot in the future.

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:46.559
So these happen after RStudio Conf, after UseR, that basically a chance to get a bunch

00:02:46.559 --> 00:02:50.880
of people interested in the Tidyverse or contributing to the Tidyverse in a room with

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:57.880
helpers and we do a bunch of PRs to fix a bunch of issues.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:03.759
You might also notice that there was a big jump in kind of May of 2018.

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:06.839
I did a little investigation to figure out what this was.

00:03:06.839 --> 00:03:12.880
This was actually me going into a PR closing, merging frenzy in ggplot2.

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:15.600
So there are a lot of PRs that have just been sitting there.

00:03:15.639 --> 00:03:22.080
So we got about like 20 new contributors in one day because I merged all those PRs.

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:28.240
A few highlights of this year, I think, really excited that we now have a paper that you

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:36.279
can cite if you want to cite the entire Tidyverse, which you can get by using the citation function.

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:40.399
The kind of idea of that paper is that rather than having to cite every package you might

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:43.199
use individually, there's just like one place you can cite.

00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:46.119
It's a published article in the Journal of Open Source Software.

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:52.600
It's kind of, I have to admit that I'm like slightly addicted to checking the citation

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:53.600
count.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:56.479
Like, you know, normally when you check the citation count of a paper, it like changes

00:03:56.479 --> 00:04:02.320
like maybe once every six months or something, but we've already had like 17 citations in

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:06.880
the two months it's been published, which is really, really amazing.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:10.399
Also we introduced embracing the double parentheses.

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:14.160
I'll talk about that a little bit later, but part of our efforts to make kind of tidy

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.600
evaluation easier and more approachable so you don't have to learn about all the theory

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:19.519
in order to use it.

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:28.359
The Vectors package, which is a bit of a mystifying package in some ways because if Vectors is

00:04:28.359 --> 00:04:33.399
successful in its goals, you will never know that it exists.

00:04:33.399 --> 00:04:38.320
And the goal of Vectors really is just to make things work more consistently behind

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:43.559
the scenes so that when you use a function in one package, you know, your predictions

00:04:43.559 --> 00:04:47.480
about functions in other packages are more likely to be correct.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:49.799
That's the main impact for like data scientists.

00:04:49.799 --> 00:04:54.480
If you're a developer as well, it makes it much, much easier to create new types of S3

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:55.480
Vectors.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:05:01.200
So if you have a new type of thing, something that makes sense as a column in the data frame,

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:04.519
Vectors provides a really nice set of tools for this.

00:05:04.519 --> 00:05:08.480
And if you want to learn more about this, you can check out when it comes out, Jesse

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:13.679
Sadler gave a really nice talk about how you can create new types of Vectors using this

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:14.679
package.

00:05:14.679 --> 00:05:22.880
Another really cool package, which I think reflects some things, some sort of development

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:28.079
processes, some coding practices that we'll see more of in the future is the Vroom package.

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:34.720
Vroom is a really, really fast way of getting data off disk from CSV files or TSV files

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:41.239
or whatever into R. I think there are two things that are particularly interesting about

00:05:41.239 --> 00:05:42.239
it.

00:05:42.239 --> 00:05:47.000
The first is that it makes heavy use of C++ 11 behind the scenes.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.320
This is kind of our first major use of C++ 11 in the tidyverse because we've been a little

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:57.239
bit worried about whether enough people can use C++ 11, even though it is eight years

00:05:57.399 --> 00:06:00.480
after, nine years after 2011.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:05.839
But the main advantage there is it gives us really easy access to multi-threaded computation.

00:06:05.839 --> 00:06:11.040
So Vroom will use many or if not all of the cores available in your computer to speed

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:12.959
up data ingest.

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:17.880
The other thing that's really interesting about Vroom is it makes extensive use of this

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:26.760
new technology in base R called AltRIP, which allows us basically to lazily load the data

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:31.839
in the file so that if you're working with a very large data set, Vroom is only going

00:06:31.839 --> 00:06:34.799
to read in the data that you actually touch.

00:06:34.799 --> 00:06:39.799
So if you read in a 10 gigabyte file, but you only look at one column or a small set

00:06:39.799 --> 00:06:44.320
of rows, it's only going to read that data up into memory, which of course makes things

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:49.399
much faster and saves memory.

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:53.579
And then last but certainly not least, I think another big thing that's been happening this

00:06:53.579 --> 00:06:59.299
year is Max and Davis has been working on tidy models, a collection of packages to bring

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:01.179
modeling into the tidyverse.

00:07:01.179 --> 00:07:06.299
I think that's really coming up to speed this year with Julia's joining that team.

00:07:06.299 --> 00:07:10.899
And I think next year that's really, people are already using tidy models effectively,

00:07:10.899 --> 00:07:17.019
but I think in the next year, that's really going to become a killer set of tools.

00:07:17.019 --> 00:07:21.500
A few things to look forward that I'm kind of excited about for 2020, I don't want to

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:25.500
make any predictions that turn out to be famously wrong.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:32.739
I will not be declaring that 2020 is the year of anything, unless I want to kill that thing.

00:07:32.739 --> 00:07:38.940
But a few things that I'm excited about, we've been putting a bunch of work into dplyr 1.0.

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:43.260
This is kind of one of the projects, one of the first times we've done sort of like a

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:44.260
full cork press.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:50.140
So like there's been four or five people from my team working on this in various ways.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:55.420
Really new implementation, which makes it much, much easier to add new features.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:08:00.700
And it's going to provide a really, really solid base for future extensions.

00:08:00.700 --> 00:08:03.739
Also working on adding more problem-oriented documentation.

00:08:03.739 --> 00:08:09.100
I think we've always had pretty good or decent tutorials and reference implementation.

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:16.140
We're also working now more on more documentation that helps you solve specific problems.

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:19.820
Also going to see kind of less per, I think.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:24.660
If you're teaching like an intro data science course, you will teach per much, much later

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:31.579
as we provide tools to kind of eliminate the use of per for some of the most important

00:08:31.579 --> 00:08:32.580
uses.

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:37.299
So Vroom, for example, allows you to slurp up an entire directory of CSV files in a single

00:08:37.299 --> 00:08:38.299
call.

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:46.059
TidyEye has new functions for rectangling complicated or deeply nested JSON data.

00:08:46.059 --> 00:08:51.140
And dplyr is going to be bringing back the row-wise verb.

00:08:51.140 --> 00:08:57.179
So there should be many less times that you need to use per when you're doing data science.

00:08:57.179 --> 00:09:01.820
Still like really, really strongly believe in per and functional programming as a programming

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:06.479
toolkit, but you won't be forced to learn it just to do data science.

00:09:06.479 --> 00:09:09.159
And then also really excited about Google Sheets 4.

00:09:09.159 --> 00:09:14.159
We've got some really great ideas, I think, for making that even more flexible.

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:16.520
Jenny is working hard on that.

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:21.239
And I am personally really hopeful that we're going to be able to use that.

00:09:21.239 --> 00:09:27.080
So Google Sheets will be our primary kind of data source for RStudio Conf next year,

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:31.719
which will avoid a bunch of problems that we had this year with keeping data synchronized

00:09:31.719 --> 00:09:34.479
in various places.

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:38.799
So what I did really want to talk about, though, is a little bit about tidy evaluation, because

00:09:38.799 --> 00:09:41.840
I think we did make some mistakes.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:46.440
Just here's kind of a provocative question that someone asked a little while ago.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:49.320
Will tidy eval kill the tidyverse?

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:54.000
I'm pretty confident the answer is no.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.159
But just to kind of, if you haven't seen tidy evaluation before, this is kind of one of

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:05.640
the challenges of programming with functions from dplyr and ggplot2, for example, is introducing

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:06.640
indirection.

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:13.200
In dplyr and ggplot2, normally you provide the name of the variable directly.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:19.320
But what do you do if you want the user to supply the name of the variable in a function?

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:25.159
Well, previously we had this technique where you did bang, bang, enquo, bang, bang, required

00:10:25.159 --> 00:10:30.239
that you kind of learned about the theory of quasi-quotation and enquo, made you think

00:10:30.239 --> 00:10:33.159
about these complicated things called quotiers.

00:10:33.159 --> 00:10:39.000
Now we have a system called embracing, which should allow you to solve the vast majority

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:45.760
of problems, along with a few other techniques, which means that you don't have to learn the

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:49.400
theory if you don't want to.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:53.000
So we've also been working on lots of articles to explain this.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.440
I think I have these up again at the end if you want to grab them.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:10:59.919
But I wanted to talk about kind of the mistakes we made.

00:10:59.919 --> 00:11:04.640
And I think the first mistake we made is that this problem as a whole was much, much harder

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:06.359
than we thought.

00:11:06.359 --> 00:11:12.080
And I know there have been at least like five points where I'm like, yes, we finally understand

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:13.919
how all of this should work.

00:11:13.919 --> 00:11:21.559
And on every point, I was wrong, except for today, and I'm reasonably confident, more

00:11:21.559 --> 00:11:26.080
confident than I've ever been before, basically because we've been doing a much better job,

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:29.239
I think, of creating this problem-oriented documentation.

00:11:29.239 --> 00:11:36.200
And we can see in that that we can solve the problems that most people are having.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:41.280
I think the other thing, the other mistake, the next mistake we made is the theory really

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:44.760
is like beautiful and elegant.

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:49.520
It is, I think, pretty much unique amongst programming languages, because very few programming

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:55.760
languages have the combination of first-class environments and computing on the language.

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:59.119
And this just adds, like, it's sort of really interesting.

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:00.640
And I think it's really cool.

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:05.000
And Leonel has worked on this a lot with me, thinks it's really cool.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.320
But most other people do not think it's really cool.

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.799
So totally, I think it's totally still worth it if you want to learn about the theory,

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:15.080
because you want to learn more about how these things work.

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:18.599
But generally, kind of the cost-benefit ratio, if you're like a data scientist just trying

00:12:18.599 --> 00:12:22.599
to solve some problem, the cost-benefit for, like, spending the time to learn the theory

00:12:22.599 --> 00:12:24.320
just wasn't there.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:27.359
And then I think we also ended up, like, introducing too much.

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:30.119
We wanted to be, like, precise.

00:12:30.119 --> 00:12:39.039
And so we ended up creating a lot of vocabulary that just ended up overwhelming people.

00:12:39.039 --> 00:12:46.000
So I think two of the kind of takeaway messages with this, like, I think one, just being aware

00:12:46.039 --> 00:12:48.559
of the problem, I think, is important.

00:12:48.559 --> 00:12:52.159
So that we are now kind of more aware that there are things that, like, we get excited

00:12:52.159 --> 00:12:56.640
about that are, like, really exciting to us, but we know, like, the rest of the R community

00:12:56.640 --> 00:12:59.559
are not going to be very excited about them.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:05.400
So we're going to try and make it more clear, like, what is the status of various things

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:06.400
that we're working on?

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:09.320
Is this something that we think is really cool, but it's pretty experimental?

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.159
Maybe it's going to change radically?

00:13:11.159 --> 00:13:14.840
Or is this something that's, like, we now have kind of grave doubts about, and maybe

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:18.119
it's on its way out in the future?

00:13:18.119 --> 00:13:23.239
And sort of and think about how can we get feedback on ideas that need more feedback

00:13:23.239 --> 00:13:28.440
without forcing, like, everyone to have to think about those issues.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:35.000
And one of the ways we're doing that is trying to be more clear about where functions live

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
in the kind of the life cycle of a function.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.679
So what is the life cycle of a function?

00:13:41.679 --> 00:13:46.400
Well, the place where most functions live is this kind of stable life cycle.

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:51.239
Like, we're pretty confident, like, this is a function, like, it does what it says on

00:13:51.239 --> 00:13:52.239
the can.

00:13:52.239 --> 00:13:53.239
It's useful.

00:13:53.239 --> 00:13:55.599
We don't think it's going to change majorly.

00:13:55.599 --> 00:13:59.799
Some functions, like, when we introduce them, we're, like, seems like a good idea.

00:13:59.799 --> 00:14:04.919
You know, I think, like, when I first introduced the when we first started introducing the

00:14:04.919 --> 00:14:08.559
pipe, like, I was, like, well, this seems like a really cool idea, but, like, no one's

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:11.239
going to understand how it works.

00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:12.799
And it turns out, like, it doesn't actually matter.

00:14:12.799 --> 00:14:14.960
The pipe is useful because it does something.

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:17.799
It allows you to write code in a really clear way.

00:14:17.799 --> 00:14:20.719
It doesn't actually matter if you don't understand how it works.

00:14:20.719 --> 00:14:22.640
You can still use it.

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:27.640
There are other things that we have kind of so sometimes, you know, we think we have a

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:34.200
really good idea, and then later on we're, like, hmm, maybe that wasn't such a good idea.

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:37.840
And so we're starting to label those functions now with questioning.

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:41.119
We're not sure if those functions are a good idea or not.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.320
Now, sometimes we'll, like, think about it more, and we'll end up back in stable.

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:49.880
Other times we'll be, like, oh, okay, we finally figured out a better way to implement this

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:53.919
function or a better way to solve this problem, and those functions become superseded.

00:14:53.919 --> 00:15:00.239
So just to give you kind of an example of this in dply 1.0, there were two functions,

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:04.679
row wise and do, that a lot of people really liked that have been in questioning for a

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:05.679
while.

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:09.479
We kind of figured out, like, row wise actually can go back to being stable.

00:15:09.479 --> 00:15:13.640
I figured out why I didn't like it and fixed that problem so it's stable again.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:17.479
Do we figured out a better way of solving, and so that becomes superseded.

00:15:17.479 --> 00:15:20.960
So superseded functions I'll talk about a little bit more shortly.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.960
These are functions, like, we don't think they're the best solution anymore, but they're

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:26.080
not going away.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:28.960
We've got, like, a better approach, but you don't need to worry that if you're using these

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:32.799
functions that we're going to yank the rug out from under you.

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:36.960
We're not going to the only time a function is when we want to be clear that a function

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:37.960
is going away.

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:42.679
We'll tell you it's deprecated, and then when eventually it gets removed altogether, then

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:45.080
it becomes defunct.

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:50.640
So just to kind of contrast deprecated and superseded a little bit more clearly, a deprecated

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:56.559
function is, like, clearly on its way out in the near future, which kind of probably

00:15:56.559 --> 00:15:59.239
means in the next year or two.

00:15:59.239 --> 00:16:01.359
You'll be warned when you use it.

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:05.320
So whenever you use a deprecated function, you will get a warning.

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:07.640
Only you get that warning, like, once per session.

00:16:07.640 --> 00:16:11.359
I think maybe that's not warning you, like, quite enough.

00:16:11.359 --> 00:16:14.640
We don't want to warn you every time you use it, because if we warn you every time you

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:18.559
use it, it's basically just as annoying as, like, taking the function away in the first

00:16:18.559 --> 00:16:19.559
place.

00:16:19.559 --> 00:16:21.640
So we're still working on trying to get that balance right.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:26.760
Like, how do we, like, gently nudge you that maybe you should be moving away from this

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:31.320
function without, like, getting in your face all the time?

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:36.760
So two examples of that, like, the tbldf function in dply, which is one way you used

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:42.200
to create tbls before we called them tbls, is on its way out.

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:46.320
Another function is dply do.

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:51.239
Generally, these functions, we won't go from, like, it will try, unless it's, like, a very

00:16:51.239 --> 00:16:55.760
niche function, it will not go from stable to deprecated immediately.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:59.320
Normally, it will go through a questioning phase first, just to make sure.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.719
So we've got plenty of notice if we're uncertain about something.

00:17:02.719 --> 00:17:08.000
Now, to contrast this, we're talking about the superseded life cycle.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.760
We've also called this retired in the past.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:15.040
My sort of thinking was, like, you know, when you retire, you're not, like, actively working

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:22.599
anymore, but you're still a productive member of society, but when people heard that a function

00:17:22.599 --> 00:17:27.839
was retired, they're, like, oh, they're going to take it out back and shoot it in the head.

00:17:27.839 --> 00:17:32.319
So we're changing the name to superseded to make it clear that we think there's a better

00:17:32.319 --> 00:17:36.599
alternative, an alternative that's, like, maybe easier to use or faster or easier to

00:17:36.599 --> 00:17:43.280
learn or more powerful or something, and we think you should learn that new approach when

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:45.839
you've got some free time.

00:17:45.839 --> 00:17:48.640
So these superseded functions, they're not going anywhere.

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:53.959
They're going to hang around for a long time, but they're not going to get any new features,

00:17:53.959 --> 00:17:56.959
and they'll only receive, like, really critical bug fixes.

00:17:57.079 --> 00:18:02.239
So a really good example of this, spread and gather and reshape and tidy are, you know,

00:18:02.239 --> 00:18:06.719
like, you know, they've been around for a long time, hundreds of thousands of people

00:18:06.719 --> 00:18:08.000
rely on them.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.079
We think we've got a better approach with pivot longer and pivot wider, an approach

00:18:12.079 --> 00:18:16.839
that hopefully you can actually remember how to use, but spread and gather are not going

00:18:16.839 --> 00:18:17.839
away.

00:18:17.839 --> 00:18:22.800
They will probably eventually go away, but that's, in this case of spread and gather,

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:24.760
probably at least five years away.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:26.959
So we do encourage you to switch.

00:18:26.959 --> 00:18:31.959
We will change them in our documentation, in our books, so that you don't, that we don't

00:18:31.959 --> 00:18:37.479
teach them, we don't advise them, but those functions will live on for a long time.

00:18:37.479 --> 00:18:40.839
And then on the other end of the spectrum, we've got these experimental functions.

00:18:40.839 --> 00:18:44.400
These are functions that, like, we have played around with internally, and we think they're

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:49.839
kind of interesting or kind of cool, but we're not, like, 100% sure about them.

00:18:49.839 --> 00:18:52.119
So maybe they'll go away, maybe they'll stay.

00:18:52.119 --> 00:18:53.640
We just don't know.

00:18:53.640 --> 00:19:00.760
And so we kind of want you, if you are adventurous, we want you to try these functions out and,

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:04.400
like, tell us, like, are these functions, do you love this function, do you hate this

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:06.520
function, like, what's going on?

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:10.959
So we can use that to kind of inform our decisions.

00:19:10.959 --> 00:19:15.140
But don't use them in critical code, like, they may get removed in the future.

00:19:15.140 --> 00:19:18.439
Don't rely on them 100%.

00:19:18.439 --> 00:19:22.280
But if they are useful to a lot of people, we will, you know, we'll keep them around

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:27.000
and hopefully remove that experimental label.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:32.800
And really all of this is kind of in service between this tension, like, we want to give

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:38.880
you a stable foundation that you can build upon and rely upon, but at the same time,

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:43.760
like, just because design is fundamentally iterative, we know we can't get it right the

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:45.280
first time.

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:51.760
And sometimes we want to be able to have a go at it a few times before we are confident.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:55.839
So we really want to just make it clear, like, where functions are on this so we can

00:19:55.839 --> 00:20:01.439
continue to build the stable foundation while trying to get it right in the long term.

00:20:01.439 --> 00:20:06.560
So just to finish up, I think the big message is here, Tidyverse seems to be doing pretty

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:07.560
well.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:09.439
Lots more contributors.

00:20:09.439 --> 00:20:13.280
Really excited about how the community is contributing to the Tidyverse.

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:17.199
You know, we messed up with tidy eval, but I think we've learned from it.

00:20:17.199 --> 00:20:21.560
And one of those things that we've learned is that making it more clear what the life

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:26.800
cycle is will hopefully make it easier for other people to know, like, what's going on.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:27.800
Thank you.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:28.800
Thanks, Hadley.

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:42.479
We have time for a couple of questions, but if yours don't get asked, I'm sure Hadley's

00:20:42.479 --> 00:20:47.880
really easy to find and has free time to ask him afterwards.

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:50.959
Is Vroom eventually replacing Redar?

00:20:50.959 --> 00:20:51.959
Yes.

00:20:51.959 --> 00:20:57.119
So Vroom will not replace Redar so much as Redar will use this Vroom under the hood.

00:20:57.119 --> 00:21:02.959
So in the long run, you will just use Redar and it will use the fast Vroom code.

00:21:02.959 --> 00:21:07.000
That should hopefully happen in the next year.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:08.239
Why less Perl?

00:21:08.239 --> 00:21:09.239
It's awesome.

00:21:09.239 --> 00:21:10.239
Yeah, yeah.

00:21:10.439 --> 00:21:17.839
Perl, yes, Perl absolutely is awesome.

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:22.400
But I think one thing we see when teaching newcomers to data science, there are a few

00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:27.319
things that you just want to be able to deal with, like that you've got a directory full

00:21:27.319 --> 00:21:28.319
of CSV files.

00:21:28.319 --> 00:21:30.719
Like, that is such a common problem.

00:21:30.719 --> 00:21:35.479
It's really nice to be able to deal with that before teaching about functions or functional

00:21:35.479 --> 00:21:37.920
programming or iteration.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:44.400
So for the most important tools, I think having some high-level way to express what you want

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:46.439
is a little bit easier.

00:21:46.439 --> 00:21:52.920
It's not about not teaching Perl, it's about teaching Perl kind of later in the curriculum.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:54.839
So it's still really, really powerful.

00:21:54.839 --> 00:21:56.160
I still love Perl.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:22:02.000
It's not going away, but we're not forcing quite as many people to use it.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:10.680
Will there be a tidyverse solution to interactive web graphics, ggplot3, question mark?

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:16.680
Thomas and I are arguing about that already, so maybe.

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:20.319
Interactive graphics is still something that's very near and dear to my heart.

00:22:20.319 --> 00:22:28.000
I think we now understand some of the data structures, understand how we could fix some

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:29.400
of the mistakes in ggplot2.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:35.160
But it just doesn't still feel to me quite like the bottleneck, like the critical problem

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:38.920
that we need to solve next, but hopefully in the long term.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:44.839
And then last one I think we have time for is, will Vroom be faster than Freed and DataTable?

00:22:44.839 --> 00:22:50.800
Vroom is already faster than DataTable for some circumstances, basically because it's

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:53.079
fast because it's lazy.

00:22:53.079 --> 00:22:59.079
It doesn't do as much work as DataTable's Freed if you don't have to work with all of

00:22:59.079 --> 00:23:00.280
the data and the data set.

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:04.439
So if you go to the Vroom website, Jim Hister, who's the author of Vroom, put together a

00:23:04.439 --> 00:23:05.680
bunch of benchmarks.

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:09.680
You can see where it does better than Freed, where it does worse than Freed.

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:13.239
Well, thank you so much, Hadley.

00:23:13.239 --> 00:23:13.520
Thank you.

